Make tea ink (or paint) for your art! 🫖 
Steep 10 black tea bags in 4 cups of hot water for 20-30 minutes. Remove the bags and simmer off half the tea. Whisk in a generous pinch of corn flour (aka corn starch in the US) and use it as you will! 
☕️ 
Did you know the Irish are the #2 consumers of tea in the world?! (Do you know who #1 is?) So I’m using a lot of tea in my art during my residency here in Galway, Ireland. 
LMK how you use your tea ink!
🖋️

Hey I’m 48 today! 🎉 We went to MoMA yesterday to see @yokoono “Bottoms” short film and it was awesome 🍑 Did I ever tell you I’m obsessed with Yoko? 🐞 Performance artist, singer-songwriter, filmmaker, activist… and yes, once married to a Beatle.

🖼️ my adorable husband 🎁 me this sweatshirt from @sororitees_bynature I’ve been wanting for ages (thanks @jilllindseystore for stocking the best women-owned brands that inspire!!) and last night I had dinner with an old friend who gave me this book I need to read immediately… “Why Have There Been No Great Women Artists” by Linda Nochlin. 
👑
As we exited through the MoMA gift shop I spied @jerrysaltz new book ART IS LIFE, which I’m also psyched to read. He’s a great follow if you want to learn more about art from an unpretentious critic. 
🎨 🖊️ 
I’m off to the studio - how else does an artist celebrate her birthday and being alive!?

Angry? Me too. Art + activism are my anger management…I try to use it as a tool of focus to make art rather than a self harming overwhelm, chaos trigger. I’ve had a complicated relationship with my anger, but in middle age have gotten better at using it to stand up for Justice. Getting into action is better for me, and the world, than devolving into a puddle of angry tears. Oh the tears still come, and I still get depressed, but more often I pick up a phone, make calls to my elected officials, made a sign and go to a protest, give money to places like @brigidalliance or @callenlorde that are organized and doing front-line work that matters.

To completely ban all abortions, and to go even further and ban birth control.

Live in Ohio?

Keeping an art journal (aka sketchbook) has been a game-changer for me…
🖊️ 
Here are 7 reasons I love to have an art journal close at hand (+ tips)… 💫 
1️⃣ Inspiration Station: 🌈✨ Your art journal is a stockpile of ideas. I prefer to alter old books with a layer of gesso or collage, as it keeps me free of “blank page” anxiety.
2️⃣ Skill Sharpening: 🔪 An art journal is like a gym for your artistic muscles. Regular practice ⬆️ your skills. 
3️⃣ Open Up Your Creativity: 🎨🌟 In an art journal there are no rules. It’s a safe haven for you to explore different styles, techniques, and mediums. (as you can see I’m ALL OVER THE PLACE)
4️⃣ Memorable Moments: 📸 An art journal is a time capsule to capture your journey as an artist. It’s a remarkable visual diary that reflects your growth and experiences.
5️⃣ Problem-Solving Playground: 🧩💡 We all get stuck with creative blocks. Fear not! Your trusty book is a good place to brainstorm… just doodle and play around.
6️⃣ Portable Pal: 🌍🚀 Your sketchbook can go anywhere… Mine fits in my bag, ready to capture small moments of inspiration on the subway, in a coffee shop, or out in nature in an NYC park. 
7️⃣ Self-Expression Sanctuary: 🌟💖 You don’t have to share your art journal with anyone. Use it to tell your story, express your feelings, and create art that resonates with your soul. Let your art journal be a true reflection of YOU.
So, my friends, those are the incredible benefits of keeping a sketchbook. It’s a magical portal to artistic exploration, growth, and self-expression. Now, join me as I flip through the pages of my filled sketchbook, and let the art speak for itself! 🎉📚✨ #SketchbookJourney #ArtisticAdventures

Art + Activism: Creatives, Women + the Fight for Abortion Care

As we celebrate the power of art and the vital role of artists in shaping our society, let’s take a moment to reflect on how art can be a driving force in the fight for women’s rights, particularly in the context of abortion care in America.

In the hit TV show “The Americans,” Margo Martindale’s character delivered a powerful message that resonates even today. American women can’t simply wait for someone else to grant us our rights; we must take them, claim them, every second of every day. And what better way to seize these rights than through the incredible strength of art + its transformative impact on minds + hearts?

Artists (in this case writers - go @wgaeast @wgadailypicket @wgastrikeunite + actors @sagaftra!) have long been at the forefront of social change, using their creative talents to challenge norms, spark dialogue, and shine a light on those whose voices have been silenced.

The struggle for reproductive rights is no different. 

Through thought-provoking TV and film characters, striking visual art, poignant literature, and evocative performances, artists can highlight the importance of reproductive autonomy and the right to make choices about our own bodies.

I’m trying to do the same with the Abortion Trading Cards, which I will have a BIG announcement about any day… (follow @rowhousepub!!)

Art has the unique ability to humanize complex issues and tell the stories that need to be heard. It can capture the emotions, struggles, and triumphs of real women, making their experiences impossible to ignore. Artists can use their craft to amplify the voices of millions of women who demand control over their reproductive destinies.

In this ongoing battle, we must unite as a society to challenge stigma and ensure access to safe and legal abortion care. It’s crucial to support and uplift the artists who champion this cause, as they play a crucial role in educating, inspiring, and mobilizing communities.

Let’s celebrate the creativity of artists who confront the challenges of all oppressed people seeking their rights.
